## ğŸ§  1. What is an Array?

### âœ… Definition:

An array is a special object in JavaScript that allows us to store **ordered collections of data**, like numbers, strings, objects, or even other arrays.

> Arrays are **zero-indexed**, **mutable**, and **dynamic** (can grow/shrink at runtime).

### ğŸ” Type:

```js
typeof [] // "object"
Array.isArray([]) // true âœ… recommended way to check
```

---

## ğŸ”¢ 2. Array Creation Methods

### âœ… Using Literal (Most Common)

```js
let fruits = ["apple", "banana", "cherry"];
```

### âœ… Using Constructor

```js
let arr = new Array(5); // [ <5 empty items> ]
let arr2 = new Array(1, 2, 3); // [1, 2, 3]
```

### âœ… Empty Array

```js
let emptyArr = [];
```

---

## ğŸ§¾ 3. Accessing Elements

```js
let arr = ["a", "b", "c"];
console.log(arr[0]); // a
console.log(arr[arr.length - 1]); // c
```

> ğŸš¨ Out-of-bound access returns `undefined`.

---

## ğŸ“ 4. Array Properties

| Property | Description        | Example                |
| -------- | ------------------ | ---------------------- |
| `length` | Number of elements | `[1, 2, 3].length â†’ 3` |

```js
let arr = [10, 20, 30];
console.log(arr.length); // 3
```

---

## ğŸ› ï¸ 5. Basic Methods (CRUD)

### ğŸ“Œ Adding Elements

| Method      | Description      |
| ----------- | ---------------- |
| `push()`    | Add to **end**   |
| `unshift()` | Add to **start** |

```js
let nums = [1, 2];
nums.push(3);       // [1, 2, 3]
nums.unshift(0);    // [0, 1, 2, 3]
```

### ğŸ§¹ Removing Elements

| Method    | Description           |
| --------- | --------------------- |
| `pop()`   | Remove from **end**   |
| `shift()` | Remove from **start** |

```js
nums.pop();         // [0, 1, 2]
nums.shift();       // [1, 2]
```

---

## ğŸ§° 6. Intermediate Methods

### ğŸ§ª `indexOf()` & `includes()`

```js
let colors = ["red", "green", "blue"];
console.log(colors.indexOf("green")); // 1
console.log(colors.includes("yellow")); // false
```

### ğŸ”§ `splice(start, deleteCount, ...items)`

Modifies the original array.

```js
let names = ["Ram", "Shyam", "Geeta"];
names.splice(1, 1, "Mohan"); 
// Remove 1 item at index 1, add "Mohan"
// ["Ram", "Mohan", "Geeta"]
```

### ğŸ” `slice(start, end)` â€“ Non-destructive

```js
let nums = [10, 20, 30, 40];
console.log(nums.slice(1, 3)); // [20, 30]
```

### ğŸ¯ `concat()` â€“ Merge arrays

```js
let a = [1, 2], b = [3, 4];
let c = a.concat(b); // [1, 2, 3, 4]
```

---

## ğŸ§  7. Traversing Arrays

### âœ… for loop

```js
for (let i = 0; i < arr.length; i++) {
  console.log(arr[i]);
}
```

### âœ… for...of

```js
for (let val of arr) {
  console.log(val);
}
```

### âœ… forEach()

```js
arr.forEach((val, idx) => console.log(`Index ${idx} = ${val}`));
```

---

## ğŸ” 8. Transforming Arrays (Functional Programming)

### ğŸ”· map() â€“ transforms and returns a new array

```js
let nums = [1, 2, 3];
let doubled = nums.map(x => x * 2); // [2, 4, 6]
```

### ğŸ”¶ filter() â€“ returns elements that match condition

```js
let odds = nums.filter(x => x % 2 !== 0); // [1, 3]
```

### ğŸ§® reduce() â€“ reduce to a single value

```js
let sum = nums.reduce((acc, val) => acc + val, 0); // 6
```

### ğŸ” find() â€“ returns first match

```js
let res = nums.find(x => x > 2); // 3
```

---

## ğŸ§® 9. Sorting Arrays

### Default Sort â€“ Lexicographical (not numeric!)

```js
let nums = [10, 5, 1];
nums.sort(); // [1, 10, 5] ğŸ˜¨
```

### Numeric Sort

```js
nums.sort((a, b) => a - b); // [1, 5, 10]
```

### Descending

```js
nums.sort((a, b) => b - a);
```

---

## ğŸ”„ 10. Reversing Arrays

```js
let arr = [1, 2, 3];
arr.reverse(); // [3, 2, 1]
```

---

## ğŸ“¦ 11. Join and Split

```js
let words = ["I", "love", "JS"];
let sentence = words.join(" "); // "I love JS"
```

---

## ğŸ§± 12. Multidimensional Arrays

```js
let matrix = [
  [1, 2],
  [3, 4],
];

console.log(matrix[1][0]); // 3
```

---

## ğŸš€ 13. Spread and Rest

### âœ… Spread (`...`)

```js
let a = [1, 2];
let b = [...a, 3]; // [1, 2, 3]
```

### âœ… Rest (`...`)

```js
function sum(...nums) {
  return nums.reduce((a, b) => a + b);
}
```

---

## ğŸ’¡ 14. Destructuring Arrays

```js
let [first, second] = [10, 20];
```

Swapping variables:

```js
let a = 1, b = 2;
[a, b] = [b, a];
```

---

## ğŸ§¬ 15. Advanced Use-Cases

### ğŸ” Flatten an array

```js
let nested = [1, [2, [3, [4]]]];
let flat = nested.flat(2); // [1, 2, 3, [4]]
```

### ğŸ“Œ Remove duplicates

```js
let unique = [...new Set([1, 2, 2, 3])]; // [1, 2, 3]
```

### ğŸ§¹ Remove falsy values

```js
let arr = [0, 1, "", false, 5];
let cleaned = arr.filter(Boolean); // [1, 5]
```

